<p class="body">Laurina is the coffee that shouldn't work. Naturally low in caffeine — the compound that helps protect coffee plants from insects — it's fragile, low-yielding, and expensive to grow at any scale. Most farmers who've tried it have abandoned it. The few who've stayed with it have produced some of the most singular cups in specialty coffee.</p>

<p class="body">For roasters building a lineup of rare single origins, Laurina occupies a category of its own. This guide covers everything you need to know: what Laurina is, how it performs in the roaster and in the cup, how to source it, and why the supply will always be limited.</p>

<h2 class="section-head">What Is <em>Laurina Coffee?</em></h2>

<p class="body">Laurina — also written as Laurina and sold under the traditional name Bourbon Pointu — is a natural genetic mutation of the Bourbon variety of Arabica coffee. It was first cultivated on the island of Réunion (then called Bourbon) in the 18th century, where it was prized for its sweetness and unusual pointed bean shape. By the 20th century, production had nearly vanished — outcompeted by higher-yielding varieties and its own susceptibility to pests.</p>

<p class="body">What makes Laurina botanically unusual is the source of its rarity: the plant produces significantly less caffeine than standard Arabica. This isn't a processing effect — it's genetics. The Laurina plant carries a mutation that limits caffeine biosynthesis. The result is a bean that contains approximately 0.4-0.6% caffeine by dry weight, compared to 1.2-1.5% for standard Arabica and 2.2-2.7% for Robusta.</p>

