<p class="body">That caffeine deficit is both Laurina's most marketable feature and its agricultural curse. Caffeine acts as a natural insecticide — plants produce it partly as a defense mechanism against pests. Laurina, with far less of it, requires more intensive pest management and more careful cultivation than standard varieties. Lower caffeine also contributes to a different flavor chemistry: less bitterness, more natural sweetness, and a delicacy that experienced cuppers compare to a refined Geisha.</p>

<h2 class="section-head">Flavor Profile: <em>What Roasters Are Buying</em></h2>

<p class="body">The El Quetzal Laurina cups with notes of apricot and raspberry up front, lemon zest in the mid-palate, milk chocolate sweetness, and a white tea quality at finish that's genuinely unusual in coffee. The body is silky, the acidity is clean and gentle, and there's an absence of bitterness that surprises roasters tasting it for the first time.</p>

<div class="callout">
  <p>Many specialty roasters compare Laurina to a refined Geisha — but with softer edges, more nuance, and a tea-like quality that sets it apart. For roasters building a lineup of rare single origins, Laurina occupies a category of its own.</p>
</div>

<p class="body">The low bitterness is structural, not just a function of roast level. Because caffeine contributes significantly to perceived bitterness in coffee, Laurina cups sweeter and cleaner than most coffees at comparable roast levels. This means roasters can go slightly darker than they might with a Geisha without losing the delicacy — though lighter profiles still express the most distinctive qualities.</p>

<h2 class="section-head">How to <em>Roast Laurina</em></h2>

<p class="body">Laurina's small bean size and relatively dense structure (it's SHG — Strictly Hard Bean) requires attention to heat application in the roaster. The beans are physically distinctive: pointed ends, smaller screen size than most Arabica varieties, with a slightly different color development curve.</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">Roast development</h3>
<p class="body">Target City to City+ for most applications. The goal is to develop the sugars enough to produce body and sweetness without flattening the stone fruit and tea notes that make Laurina worth the premium. Charge temperature and first crack timing will depend on your specific roaster, but the general principle: more development time relative to total roast time than you'd give a washed Ethiopian, less than you'd give a Brazilian natural.</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">Grind adjustment</h3>
<p class="body">Laurina's smaller bean size means grinders may need slight adjustment — particularly for espresso, where uniformity matters more. Dial your grinder with a fresh sample rather than assuming your usual espresso settings will transfer.</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">Extraction parameters</h3>
<p class="body">Pour-over: 1:15 ratio, 195-200°F, extended bloom (45-60 seconds) to highlight natural sweetness. Espresso: 18g in, 36g out, 28-32 seconds. Cold brew: exceptional — the low caffeine and natural sweetness produce a smooth concentrate that works well undiluted.</p>

<h2 class="section-head">Where Laurina <em>Grows</em></h2>

<p class="body">Laurina is grown in only a handful of places worldwide. Réunion Island, where the variety originated, still produces some. Brazil's Daterra estate has produced Laurina for research purposes. Costa Rica, Guatemala, and Indonesia have small experimental plots. And Nicaragua — specifically Finca El Quetzal in the Matagalpa highlands — has emerged as one of the most compelling sources available to US roasters.</p>

<p class="body">The El Quetzal Laurina grows at 1,200+ MASL on volcanic soil, shade-grown under eucalyptus canopies planted in the 1960s. The farm has produced specialty coffee continuously since 1947 — four generations of the Bendaña McEwan family cultivating the same hillsides. The Laurina parcel is one of the smallest on the farm, producing under 1,000 lbs total in 2025.</p>

<h2 class="section-head">Sourcing: <em>Where to Buy Laurina Green Coffee</em></h2>

<p class="body">Laurina green coffee is genuinely hard to source at specialty grade. Spot market availability is sporadic, lot quality varies significantly across producers, and most of the volume that exists never makes it to US roasters through accessible channels.</p>

<p class="body">El Quetzal Coffee Co. offers farm-direct Laurina green coffee at <a href="https://elquetzal.coffee/products/eq-washed-laurina-green-coffee" style="color: var(--gold); text-decoration: none;">elquetzal.coffee</a>. Samples start at 150g ($8). Full lots available in 5 lb, 10 lb, and 30 lb formats. Forward contracts for 69kg sacks are available for the 2027 harvest. Given the production scale, allocation sells out — often within days of new lot announcements.</p>

