<h2 class="section-head">Laurina vs. <em>Specialty Decaf: The Comparison Roasters Make</em></h2>

<p class="body">The most common question from roasters discovering Laurina: is it a decaf replacement? The honest answer is yes and no.</p>

<p class="body">Laurina has roughly one-third the caffeine of standard Arabica — meaningful reduction, but not zero. Guests who need true caffeine elimination for medical reasons still need decaf. But for the much larger segment of specialty coffee consumers who are caffeine-sensitive, afternoon drinkers, or simply interested in lower-stimulant options without sacrificing cup quality, Laurina is a genuinely superior product.</p>

<p class="body">The flavor advantage over even the best-quality decaf is significant. Swiss Water and CO2 decaffeination processes, which are the highest-quality methods available, still strip flavor compounds alongside caffeine. Laurina doesn't lose anything in processing because there's nothing to process. The cup you get is the full expression of the plant — sweet, complex, and delicate in ways that decaf rarely achieves.</p>

<p class="body">For specialty roasters looking to differentiate their decaf or low-caffeine offering, Laurina is the most compelling option in the market. The constraint is supply — and that supply isn't going to grow significantly anytime soon.</p>

